617</questionid><creationdate>1242680063</creationdate><lastactivity>1242680063</lastactivity><body>&lt;p&gt;If you treat the file as a byte array, then you control which order you pick the bytes out, and the endian-ness of your CPU actually ends up not mattering.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is also highly useful in terms of dealing with alignment problems.  Your core dump might concievably have unaligned references in it.  I know that's highly unlikely, but it could be due to corruption as well.  This is another problem that is avoided by treating the file as a byte array.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;I used this approach in implementing jhead.&lt;/p&gt;</body><title>Supporting byte ordering in Linux user space</title><lastedit>-1</lastedit><accepted>false</accepted></answer><answer id="879285"><ownerid>18310</ownerid><questionid>874617</questionid><creationdate>1242673869</creationdate><lastactivity>1242673869</lastactivity><body>&lt;p&gt;Based on what you're actually trying to do (read ELF core dump files without having to worry about endian issues), I believe using libelf, available &lt;a href="http://www.freebsd.org/cgi/pds.cgi?ports/devel/libelf" rel="nofollow"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; with a nice tutorial &lt;a href="http://people.freebsd.org/~jkoshy/download/libelf/article.html" rel="nofollow"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;, would be a good choice.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This library works transparently with big- and little-endian ELF files and runs just fine under Linux despite its FreeBSD origins (the usual "./configure" and "make" sequence is all you'll need to build it).  For grins I tried the "reading a program header table" example (with minor modifications to get it to build) on an x86 core file as well as a MIPS big-endian core file, it appears to "just work".&lt;/p&gt;</body><title>Supporting byte ordering in Linux user space</title><lastedit>-1</lastedit><accepted>true</accepted></answer><answer id="434403"><ownerid>13491</ownerid><questionid>434369</questionid><creationdate>1231732845</c